                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="17893640" author="emilles" created="Mon, 28 Oct 2024 22:43:55 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/apache/groovy/commit/65506f4c5808e9625a93aee8c71523c2ced1739a&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://github.com/apache/groovy/commit/65506f4c5808e9625a93aee8c71523c2ced1739a&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I went with the solution that most closely matches Java and eliminates ambiguity.  A constant-only &lt;tt&gt;enum&lt;/tt&gt; can have a trailing comma.  An &lt;tt&gt;enum&lt;/tt&gt; with constants and members requires no comma plus a newline or a semicolon for separation.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17952030" author="paulk" created="Fri, 16 May 2025 07:25:03 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=emilles&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;emilles&quot;&gt;emilles&lt;/a&gt; Is this a breaking change? I was updating the Groovy 5 release notes and can&apos;t actually see any change (breaking or otherwise).&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17952125" author="emilles" created="Fri, 16 May 2025 13:45:02 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;If I recall, there were some trailing comma cases that did work.  But to deal with the annotated method, I looked at what was possible and then compared to what Java supports.  There are a few cases of trailing comma that worked previously that will not work under this new grammar.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This might be the clearest example:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;code panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;codeContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre class=&quot;code-groovy&quot;&gt;
&lt;span class=&quot;code-comment&quot;&gt;// GROOVY-9301
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;enum&lt;/span&gt; E10 {
    X(1), Y(2), &lt;span class=&quot;code-comment&quot;&gt;// trailing comma
&lt;/span&gt;    ; &lt;span class=&quot;code-comment&quot;&gt;// added &lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;this&lt;/span&gt; to test &lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;case&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;    &lt;span class=&quot;code-object&quot;&gt;Object&lt;/span&gt; value
    E10(value) {
        &lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;this&lt;/span&gt;.value = value
    }
}
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17952321" author="paulk" created="Sat, 17 May 2025 05:23:26 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;That example seems to work fine in 4.0.26?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17952373" author="emilles" created="Sat, 17 May 2025 14:39:42 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Did you remove the semi?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17952393" author="paulk" created="Sat, 17 May 2025 23:57:40 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Okay, yes. I see the breaking part now. I am not sure what we fixed (ambiguity?).&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17952716" author="emilles" created="Mon, 19 May 2025 19:52:43 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The example of constants followed by an annotated method. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
